1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,250
If you've been following this series,

2
00:00:07,550 --> 00:00:10,175
you've seen CueDeck running a single room.

3
00:00:10,475 --> 00:00:13,850
One stage, one session list, one set of transitions.

4
00:00:14,150 --> 00:00:16,150
Now let's scale it up.

5
00:00:16,450 --> 00:00:19,825
In this episode we're running a three-track conference —

6
00:00:20,125 --> 00:00:24,250
a main plenary stage and two parallel workshop rooms running simultaneously.

7
00:00:24,550 --> 00:00:27,550
This is where CueDeck's multi-room features come in.

8
00:00:27,850 --> 00:00:30,850
I'll show you how to set up rooms,

9
00:00:31,150 --> 00:00:33,775
how to filter the view per room,

10
00:00:34,075 --> 00:00:37,825
how to use the Programme signage display to show the

11
00:00:38,125 --> 00:00:41,875
full grid to attendees, and how anchor sessions keep your

12
00:00:42,175 --> 00:00:44,800
programme together when one track falls behind.

13
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:48,100
Every session in CueDeck has a Room field.

14
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:53,275
It's a free-text input — you type the room name and save it.

15
00:00:53,575 --> 00:00:55,825
There's no separate room setup required;

16
00:00:56,125 --> 00:00:59,500
the room names are generated by whatever you type.

17
00:00:59,800 --> 00:01:03,550
For a three-track event, I'd use consistent names across all

18
00:01:03,850 --> 00:01:06,475
sessions: 'Main Stage', 'Workshop A', 'Workshop B'.

19
00:01:06,775 --> 00:01:09,025
Capitalisation and spacing matter here —

20
00:01:09,325 --> 00:01:13,075
'Workshop A' and 'workshop a' would show as two separate

21
00:01:13,375 --> 00:01:17,125
rooms in the filter bar, so pick a format and

22
00:01:17,425 --> 00:01:20,050
stick with it across your whole programme.

23
00:01:20,350 --> 00:01:22,975
Once you've set rooms on your sessions,

24
00:01:23,275 --> 00:01:27,025
the filter bar at the top of the session list

25
00:01:27,325 --> 00:01:30,700
automatically generates a chip for each unique room name.

26
00:01:30,1000 --> 00:01:33,250
You don't configure this anywhere —

27
00:01:33,550 --> 00:01:35,800
it builds itself from the data.

28
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:40,600
With three rooms, you'll see three room chips in the filter bar.

29
00:01:40,900 --> 00:01:43,150
Click one to isolate that room.

30
00:01:43,450 --> 00:01:47,200
Click it again to clear the filter and see everything.

31
00:01:47,500 --> 00:01:52,375
Click Workshop A — the session list immediately shows only Workshop A sessions.

32
00:01:52,675 --> 00:01:54,675
Everything else is hidden.

33
00:01:54,975 --> 00:01:58,350
This is the primary tool for a multi-room event.

34
00:01:58,650 --> 00:02:02,400
Each stage manager running their own room filters to their

35
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:04,700
room and ignores the rest.

36
00:02:04,1000 --> 00:02:08,375
The director can see everything or filter as needed.

37
00:02:08,675 --> 00:02:12,800
The filter works alongside the status filter and the search bar.

38
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:16,100
So you can filter to Workshop A AND

39
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:19,775
only READY or LIVE sessions at the same time.

40
00:02:20,075 --> 00:02:22,700
In a large event with thirty or

41
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,375
forty sessions across five rooms, that combination is essential.

42
00:02:26,675 --> 00:02:30,050
Click another room chip to switch to that room.

43
00:02:30,350 --> 00:02:32,975
Click the active chip to deselect it.

44
00:02:33,275 --> 00:02:37,025
The filter state is persisted through the current session —

45
00:02:37,325 --> 00:02:39,950
close and reopen the context panel and

46
00:02:40,250 --> 00:02:42,250
your filter stays active.

47
00:02:42,550 --> 00:02:46,675
For a multi-room event, I typically structure the team by room.

48
00:02:46,975 --> 00:02:49,600
The director has the full view —

49
00:02:49,900 --> 00:02:51,900
all three rooms, all sessions.

50
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:55,575
Each stage manager is assigned to one room and

51
00:02:55,875 --> 00:03:00,375
filters their view to that room from the start of the day.

52
00:03:00,675 --> 00:03:04,050
They see only what they need to see and

53
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:06,350
act only on their sessions.

54
00:03:06,650 --> 00:03:08,900
The director broadcasts messages to everyone,

55
00:03:09,200 --> 00:03:11,450
monitors the full programme from above,

56
00:03:11,750 --> 00:03:14,375
and handles cross-room decisions like delay cascades.

57
00:03:14,675 --> 00:03:18,425
The stage managers handle the ground-level transitions for their room.

58
00:03:18,725 --> 00:03:20,725
This structure scales cleanly.

59
00:03:21,025 --> 00:03:24,775
Adding a fourth room means inviting one more stage manager

60
00:03:25,075 --> 00:03:27,700
and telling them their room name —

61
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
no additional setup required.

62
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:34,050
Now for one of the most important concepts in multi-room

63
00:03:34,350 --> 00:03:36,350
delay management: anchor sessions.

64
00:03:36,650 --> 00:03:39,650
An anchor session is a plenary moment —

65
00:03:39,950 --> 00:03:42,200
lunch break, networking session, closing keynote,

66
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:44,750
registration — that affects every room.

67
00:03:45,050 --> 00:03:47,675
When the main stage runs long and

68
00:03:47,975 --> 00:03:50,600
you apply a delay to Workshop A,

69
00:03:50,900 --> 00:03:54,650
the delay cascade rolls forward through that room's subsequent sessions.

70
00:03:54,950 --> 00:03:57,950
But it stops at the next anchor session.

71
00:03:58,250 --> 00:04:00,250
The anchor holds its position.

72
00:04:00,550 --> 00:04:02,550
It doesn't shift.

73
00:04:02,850 --> 00:04:06,600
Because lunch starts at thirteen hundred whether Workshop A's morning

74
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:09,525
panel ran six minutes over or not.

75
00:04:09,825 --> 00:04:13,575
The catering team, the hotel, the signage in the lobby

76
00:04:13,875 --> 00:04:17,625
— all of that is fixed to the anchor time.

77
00:04:17,925 --> 00:04:21,675
Look at what happens when I apply a five-minute delay

78
00:04:21,975 --> 00:04:23,975
to this Workshop B session.

79
00:04:24,275 --> 00:04:28,025
The sessions below it in Workshop B shift forward by

80
00:04:28,325 --> 00:04:31,700
five minutes — that's the cascade doing its job.

81
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,250
But the Networking Lunch session, which

82
00:04:34,550 --> 00:04:38,300
is marked as an anchor, stays exactly where it is.

83
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:40,850
It does not absorb the delay.

84
00:04:41,150 --> 00:04:44,900
The practical implication: your workshop sessions will need to compress

85
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:48,200
slightly before the anchor, or you accept that

86
00:04:48,500 --> 00:04:51,500
the final pre-lunch session ends a bit late.

87
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:54,050
That's a call for the director,

88
00:04:54,350 --> 00:04:58,850
and CueDeck gives you the information to make it in real time.

89
00:04:59,150 --> 00:05:02,900
Anchor sessions have a visual marker on their card —

90
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:08,075
a small indicator that tells you at a glance 'this one doesn't move'.

91
00:05:08,375 --> 00:05:12,125
Scan the session list and you can immediately see which

92
00:05:12,425 --> 00:05:15,425
sessions are the fixed points of your programme.

93
00:05:15,725 --> 00:05:20,225
The Programme display mode is the master view for a multi-track event.

94
00:05:20,525 --> 00:05:22,775
It renders a time-by-room grid —

95
00:05:23,075 --> 00:05:26,075
rows running down the left are time slots,

96
00:05:26,375 --> 00:05:29,375
columns across the top are your room names.

97
00:05:29,675 --> 00:05:33,800
Every session appears in the correct cell at the correct time.

98
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:37,850
Put this on a large screen in the main lobby

99
00:05:38,150 --> 00:05:41,900
or the registration area and attendees can see the entire

100
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:44,450
day's programme at a glance —

101
00:05:44,750 --> 00:05:47,375
every track, every room, every time slot,

102
00:05:47,675 --> 00:05:49,675
all in one view.

103
00:05:49,975 --> 00:05:53,350
As sessions go live they update in real time.

104
00:05:53,650 --> 00:05:57,400
A session that's running five minutes late will show its

105
00:05:57,700 --> 00:06:00,700
updated time if you've applied a delay cascade.

106
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:05,500
The Programme mode reads from the same session data as the console.

107
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:08,800
There's no separate configuration for the grid —

108
00:06:09,100 --> 00:06:13,225
it builds from your session room names and scheduled times automatically.

109
00:06:13,525 --> 00:06:17,275
Add a room by assigning sessions to a new room

110
00:06:17,575 --> 00:06:20,950
name, and the column appears in the Programme display.

111
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:25,375
Three practical things I've learned from running multi-room events on CueDeck.

112
00:06:25,675 --> 00:06:29,050
First: set your anchor sessions before the event starts.

113
00:06:29,350 --> 00:06:31,600
Identify all the plenary moments —

114
00:06:31,900 --> 00:06:34,525
lunch, networking breaks, the closing keynote —

115
00:06:34,825 --> 00:06:38,575
and mark them as anchors in the session edit modal.

116
00:06:38,875 --> 00:06:42,625
This takes five minutes and saves you from accidentally cascading

117
00:06:42,925 --> 00:06:45,175
a delay into a fixed point.

118
00:06:45,475 --> 00:06:49,975
Second: use room naming conventions your whole team knows before show day.

119
00:06:50,275 --> 00:06:52,900
Brief everyone: 'our rooms are Main Stage,

120
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:56,950
Workshop A, Workshop B.' One naming convention, communicated in advance.

121
00:06:57,250 --> 00:07:01,000
Third: for delay decisions, the director filters to the affected

122
00:07:01,300 --> 00:07:04,675
room, sees the cascade, decides if it's acceptable or

123
00:07:04,975 --> 00:07:06,975
needs a broadcast to attendees.

124
00:07:07,275 --> 00:07:11,025
That decision should happen within sixty seconds of the overrun

125
00:07:11,325 --> 00:07:15,075
starting — the delay cascade makes the impact visible immediately.

126
00:07:15,375 --> 00:07:20,250
Multi-room events are where CueDeck earns its place in a professional production toolkit.

127
00:07:20,550 --> 00:07:23,175
Room filters, per-room delay cascades, anchor sessions,

128
00:07:23,475 --> 00:07:27,225
and the Programme signage grid all work together to give

129
00:07:27,525 --> 00:07:31,275
you control over a complex programme without losing the overview.

130
00:07:31,575 --> 00:07:34,200
The next episode — Episode 21 —

131
00:07:34,500 --> 00:07:36,750
is the capstone of this series.

132
00:07:37,050 --> 00:07:39,300
We're running a full event, uncut,

133
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:41,850
from blank console to post-event report.

134
00:07:42,150 --> 00:07:45,900
Tech Summit 2026, ten sessions, three rooms, one live run-through.

135
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:49,950
Everything we've covered in this series in one complete demo.

136
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:52,250
I'll see you there.
